## Context System
Tiered retrieval: load what's needed, not everything.
1. Always loaded: this CLAUDE.md plus any memory files.
2. Loaded at session start: `context_index.md`, the dashboard of active workstreams.
3. On demand: `context_<workstream>.md`, loaded only when that workstream is active.

Keep the index to roughly 8 workstreams max. When a context file grows past about 500 lines or 16KB, archive the old material to `context_<workstream>_archive.md` and keep the live file lean. A session-end "wrapup" step writes state back into the relevant context file so the next session starts warm instead of re-deriving it.

## Cross-Cutting Workstreams
Launching a session from a subfolder loses root context by design. That's correct for a self-contained workstream, but wrong for one that intersects with others (e.g. a workstream that touches both `<workstream-a>` and `<workstream-b>`).

A cross-cutting workstream gets two blocks inside its OWN `<workstream>/CLAUDE.md`:
- `## Required Reading at Session Start`: a numbered list of backtick-quoted context-file paths to auto-load before doing anything else.
- `## Write Boundary`: keep deliverables inside this folder; ask before writing into a sibling workstream's folder.

See `templates/crosscutting-CLAUDE.md` for a worked example of both blocks.

## Reference (loaded on demand)
Keep this file lean. Move large lookup tables, one-off procedures, and rarely-needed reference material into a separate doc, and read it only when the task actually needs it, not on every session start.

## Naming Convention
Pattern: `[topic]_[what-it-is]_v[N].[ext]`, lowercase, hyphens inside a segment, underscores between segments.
Example: `webapp_deploy-runbook_v2.md`.

## Worktree Policy
Any code task touching 3 or more files, or requiring a multi-step plan, uses a git worktree for isolation. Single-file fixes and read-only investigation can stay in the main session.

## Verification Rules
Verify facts before recommending them: web-search product specs, prices, and versions rather than relying on memory. Never fabricate a fact; state assumptions explicitly or ask instead. Accuracy over completion.

